      <h1>Why Privacy Matters for Period Tracking Apps</h1>

      <div class="article-content">
        <p class="lead">Period tracking apps know some of the most intimate details about your life: your menstrual cycle, sexual activity, pregnancy attempts, and more. But where does all that data go?</p>

        <h2>The Data You're Sharing</h2>
        <p>When you use a typical period tracking app, you might be logging:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Menstrual cycle dates and flow intensity</li>
          <li>Sexual activity and contraception use</li>
          <li>Pregnancy tests and fertility windows</li>
          <li>Physical symptoms and moods</li>
          <li>Medications and health conditions</li>
        </ul>
        <p>This is deeply personal health information. And unlike your medical records, it often isn't protected by healthcare privacy laws.</p>

        <h2>Where Does Your Data Go?</h2>
        <p>Many popular period tracking apps have been found to share data with third parties, including:</p>

        <h3>Advertisers</h3>
        <p>Some apps share data with advertising networks. This means your cycle information could be used to target you with ads — for pregnancy tests, baby products, or fertility services.</p>

        <h3>Data Brokers</h3>
        <p>Companies that buy and sell personal information for profit. Your menstrual data could end up in profiles sold to marketers, insurers, or employers.</p>

        <h3>Social Media Platforms</h3>
        <p>Integration with Facebook and other platforms means your data can flow to them, even if you just use social login.</p>

        <h2>Real-World Consequences</h2>
        <p>This isn't just theoretical. In 2021, the FTC took action against a popular period tracking app for sharing health data with marketing companies, despite promising users their data was private.</p>

        <p>More concerning scenarios include:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Insurance implications:</strong> Health data could theoretically affect insurance rates or coverage</li>
          <li><strong>Employment:</strong> Pregnancy-related data could be valuable to employers making hiring decisions</li>
          <li><strong>Legal exposure:</strong> In some jurisdictions, cycle data has been sought in legal proceedings</li>
          <li><strong>Relationship safety:</strong> Partners or family members accessing account data</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>The "Free" App Problem</h2>
        <p>There's a saying in tech: "If you're not paying for the product, you are the product." Free apps need to make money somehow, and that often means monetizing your data.</p>

        <p>Even apps that claim not to sell your data may:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Share "anonymized" data that can be re-identified</li>
          <li>Use your data for "research" with commercial partners</li>
          <li>Change their privacy policy without meaningful notice</li>
          <li>Be acquired by companies with different data practices</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>What Real Privacy Looks Like</h2>
        <p>True privacy in a health app means:</p>

        <p><strong>No servers:</strong> Your data should never leave your device. If there's no server, there's nothing to hack, subpoena, or sell.</p>

        <p><strong>No accounts:</strong> No email, no login, no way to connect your data to your identity.</p>

        <p><strong>No analytics:</strong> Even "anonymous" usage data can reveal patterns about you.</p>

        <p><strong>No third-party code:</strong> Many apps include advertising SDKs and analytics tools that phone home constantly.</p>

        <h2>Questions to Ask Before Downloading</h2>
        <p>Before you trust an app with your health data, ask:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>Does this app require an account? Why?</li>
          <li>Where is my data stored?</li>
          <li>What third parties receive my data?</li>
          <li>Can I export and delete all my data?</li>
          <li>How does this app make money?</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout">
          <h3>Privacy Without Compromise</h3>
